  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Azito Phase 3</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IFC&apos;&apos;s involvement in this Project is expected to:  * Support the provision of least cost, reliable and clean base load power to help reduce the country&apos;&apos;s power shortage, and support its economic recovery;  * Displace expensive emergency thermal power being rented today, thus reducing costs to Ivoirian consumers; * Stimulate the entrance of new IPPs and the use of combined cycle technology, making efficient use of the country&apos;&apos;s natural gas resources (as the Project does not use additional gas);  * Provide a strong signalling effect to the broader investment community to support C&#xC3;&#xB4;te d&apos;&apos;Ivoire&apos;&apos;s economic growth.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Project consists of the expansion of the existing 2x 144MW natural gas-fired open cycle Azito power plant in C&#xF4;te dIvoire by adding 139MW steam cycle capacity, converting it into a combined cycle operation (the Project).  The Project, expected to enhance the efficiency of the existing plant by generating 50 percent more power without the use of any additional gas, will be developed, designed, constructed and operated under a 20-year Build-Own-Operate-Transfer (BOOT) arrangement.  The Project will sell its power to Government of C&#xF4;te dIvoire (GOCI) through Compagnie Ivoirienne dElectricit&#xE9; (CIE), the private transmission and distribution company.</narrative>
  </description>
